{
  "texts": [
    "In practice, however, this is usually not feasible because there are too many algorithms to try, and some of them run slowly.",
    "This problem is exacerbated especially when dealing with large amounts of data, which often occurs in knowledge discovery in databases.",
    "Many algorithm selection methods are limited to selecting a single algorithm or a small group of algorithms (Abdulrahman, 2017), that are expected to perform well on a given problem (Kalousis and Theoharis, 1999; Pfahringer and Bensusan, 2000; Todorovski, 2003).",
    "Brazdil et al. believe that the algorithm recommendation problem is more similar to the ranking task in nature, which is similar to the common ranking task in information retrieval and recommendation systems (Brazdil and Costa, 2003).",
    "In these tasks, it is not known in advance how many alternatives the user will actually consider."
  ]
}